# Licensing of PhPty

PhPty is a monorepo. Each module is a derivative of a different upstream project,
and a port is a derivative work — so the licence is not uniform across this
repository. Every module carries its own `LICENSE` file, which is authoritative
for that module and travels with it when the module is split out into its own
repository.

| Module           | Licence                     | Derived from                                                   |
| ---------------- | --------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `tty/`           | MIT                         | Original work, written against POSIX and termios documentation  |
| `pty/`           | MIT                         | Original work, written against POSIX and termios documentation  |
| `vterm/`         | MIT                         | Original work. Binds libghostty-vt (MIT, (c) 2024 Mitchell     |
|                  |                             | Hashimoto and Ghostty contributors) at runtime via FFI          |
| `screen-test/`   | MIT                         | yamatanooroti — MIT, Copyright (c) 2020 aycabta                 |
| `reline/`        | Ruby licence or BSDL (dual) | reline — Copyright (c) Yukihiro Matsumoto, and rb-readline,     |
|                  |                             | Copyright (c) 2009 Park Heesob                                  |

Reline cannot be relicensed to MIT. Upstream reline declares `license = 'Ruby'`,
a dual Ruby-licence/2-clause-BSDL grant, and it vendors rb-readline under a BSD
licence. Both notices carry through to the port.

Tty and Pty are MIT only because they are implemented from specifications
rather than transliterated from Ruby's `io-console` or `PTY`. See
`docs/adr/0004-licensing-varies-by-module.md` and
`docs/adr/0005-port-fidelity-varies-by-layer.md`.

Despite its name, `vterm/` is not derived from vterm-gem: that gem binds
libvterm, and `vterm/` binds libghostty-vt, so no aycabta code or design remains
in it. libghostty-vt is dlopen'ed at runtime and never redistributed here, which
makes it a dependency rather than an upstream.

The reference implementations under `references/` are git submodules. They are
not part of PhPty and remain under their own upstream licences.
